INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2f8b038e-95e8-40a6-9b16-34c0f092c5b0',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Phoenix Testing — Unit vs Integration, Mocking HTTP, and Sandbox Strategy$escape$,
  $escape$Phoenix separates concerns cleanly via two generated test helpers: `DataCase` (Ecto sandbox, no HTTP) and `ConnCase` (full Plug pipeline + router). `Ecto.Adapters.SQL.Sandbox` wraps each test in a transaction that rolls back automatically, enabling `async: true` without data collisions — keep it on by default.

For HTTP clients, never call HTTPoison or Req directly from business logic. Define a behaviour module, implement it in production, and inject a `Mox`-backed mock in test env via `config :my_app, :http_client, MyApp.HTTPClientMock` in `config/test.exs`. This keeps unit tests fast and deterministic. Use `Bypass` when you need to assert on real HTTP wire format — it spins up a local Cowboy instance that captures outgoing requests.

Rule of thumb: unit-test pure context functions (`MyApp.Accounts.create_user/1`); integration-test controllers and LiveViews through `ConnCase` with `Phoenix.ConnTest` helpers like `get/2` and `json_response/2`. Avoid `Sandbox.mode(:shared)` except when external OS processes (e.g., Wallaby browser tests) need DB access. `verify_on_exit!/1` in Mox ensures no unexpected calls slip through.$escape$,
  $escape$# lib/my_app/http_client.ex
defmodule MyApp.HTTPClient do
  @callback get(String.t()) :: {:ok, map()} | {:error, term()}
end

# test/support/mocks.ex
Mox.defmock(MyApp.HTTPClientMock, for: MyApp.HTTPClient)

# test/my_app/weather_test.exs
defmodule MyApp.WeatherTest do
  use MyApp.DataCase, async: true
  import Mox

  setup :verify_on_exit!

  test "fetches current temperature" do
    expect(MyApp.HTTPClientMock, :get, fn _url ->
      {:ok, %{"temp" => 72}}
    end)

    assert {:ok, %{temp: 72}} = MyApp.Weather.current("NYC")
  end
end$escape$,
